## 1\. Introduction {#1.-introduction}

### 1.1 System Overview {#1.1-system-overview}

The SafeRide V2V Enhanced System is a distributed vehicle-to-vehicle (V2V) hazard detection platform consisting of three vehicle units communicating via wireless mesh networking with one vehicle assuming the role of an ego vehicle. The system combines real-time sensor data from MPU6500 6-axis inertial measurement units, QMC5883L 3-axis magnetometers, and NEO-6M GPS modules with ESP-NOW mesh networking to enable infrastructure-free collision avoidance.

Each vehicle unit operates autonomously, collecting sensor data at 100Hz which was calculated by inspecting a real-world data recording of the sensors, output file observed a new sensor data row each 0.01 seconds confirming data collection rate of 100Hz , the ego vehicle unit performs on-device machine learning inference for hazard classification, it’s derived from broadcasting vehicles that broadcast safety messages to the ego vehicle (where the machine learning agent is active). The system is capable of detecting multiple traffic scenarios including convoy following and intersections.

### 1.2 Purpose {#1.2-purpose}

This Software Design Document provides a comprehensive technical specification for the SafeRide V2V Enhanced System. It serves as:

- Technical blueprint defining system architecture and component interactions  
- Development reference for firmware implementation  
- Integration guide documenting hardware and software interfaces  
- Validation basis for verifying implementation correctness  
- Maintenance support for future system modifications

The document translates functional and non-functional requirements from the SRS into concrete design decisions.

### 1.3 Scope {#1.3-scope}

**In Scope:**

- Firmware architecture for ESP32-based vehicle units  
- Sensor integration (MPU6500 IMU, QMC5883L magnetometer, NEO-6M GPS)  
- ESP-NOW mesh networking protocol implementation  
- V2V message format and communication design  
- On-device machine learning inference architecture  
- Data logging system for training data collection  
- Multi-scenario hazard detection algorithms

**Out of Scope:**

- Cloud-based services or mobile applications  
- Production safety certification  
- Vehicle actuation or autonomous control  
- Additional sensor types (camera, radar, LIDAR)

## 2\. System Architecture {#2.-system-architecture}

### 2.1 Architectural Description and Design: Roles, Activities and Data {#2.1-architectural-description-and-design:-roles,-activities-and-data}

#### 2.1.1 High-Level Architecture {#2.1.1-high-level-architecture}

The SafeRide V2V system employs a distributed multi-vehicle architecture ESP32-based units communicate via ESP-NOW mesh networking to enable collision detection and driver alerts. The system is organized across three architectural tiers:

**Tier 1: Vehicle Fleet & Intelligence Layer**  
\- V001 (Ego Car): The intelligent follower vehicle equipped with:

- DataLogger  Records received V2V messages from V002/V003 plus ego vehicle speed to SD card for ML training dataset generation  
- AlertManager: Provides driver feedback via LED patterns and buzzer alerts

 \- V002 & V003 (Lead Vehicles): Broadcast-only vehicles that transmit position, speed, and sensor data via V2V messages

**Tier 2: Firmware Layer (Distributed)**  
 Each vehicle runs identical Package Manager Firmware responsible for:

-  Message Broadcasting: Transmitting V2VMessage packets (SAE J2735 BSM format, 90 bytes) every 100ms  
- Message Reception: Receiving and parsing V2V messages from peer vehicles  
- Deduplication: Filtering duplicate packets using sourceMAC \+ timestamp tracking  
- Sensor Integration: Aggregating data from MPU6500 (6-axis IMU), NEO-6M GPS, and QMC5883L magnetometer


**Tier 3: Hardware Layer**  
\- ESP32 Microcontroller: each equipped with:  
\- MPU6500 6-axis IMU (I²C, pins 21/22)  
\- NEO-6M GPS module (UART, pins 16/17, requires 5V power)  
\- QMC5883L magnetometer (I²C, pins 21/22)  
\- SD card module (SPI, CS=5) \- Ego Car only  
\- Status LED (GPIO 2\) and calibration button (GPIO 0\)  
 \- ESP-NOW Mesh Network: 2.4GHz peer-to-peer communication (250-byte payload, \<50ms latency, \~100m range)

## ![][image3]

#### 2.1.2 Layer Responsibilities {#2.1.2-layer-responsibilities}

**Application Layer** maintains vehicle state from all sensors, orchestrates hazard detection workflow, manages LED alert patterns based on risk levels, and controls main loop timing.  
**Machine Learning Layer** extracts features from sensor and peer vehicle data, executes quantized TFLite model inference, classifies hazard by braking alerts configured at several braking-levels.  
**Network Layer** implements ESP-NOW broadcast communication, serializes V2VMessage structures, handles message deduplication via MAC+timestamp, and manages mesh relay.  
**Sensor Layer** abstracts hardware-specific sensor access, provides calibrated data in standard units, implements GPS caching for intermittent signal, and handles sensor fusion for heading combines magnetometer data with accelerometer (and optionally gyroscope) measurements to produce a tilt-compensated, calibrated, and stable yaw angle suitable for V2V safety logic.

#### 2.1.3 Component Roles {#2.1.3-component-roles}

| Component | Role | Primary Activities |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| MPU6500Driver | Motion Sensing | Read acceleration/rotation, calibrate offsets |
| QMC5883LDriver | Heading Sensing | Read magnetic field, calculate compass heading |
| NEO6M\_Driver | Position Sensing | Parse NMEA, calculate GPS heading, cache position |
| EspNowTransport | Communication | Initialize ESP-NOW, broadcast/receive messages |
| PackageManager | Message Handling | Deduplicate, track sources, enforce limits |
| V2VMessage | Data Structure | Serialize state, validate integrity, check staleness |
| DataLogger | Data Collection | Write CSV to SD card, buffer writes, manage sessions |
| FeatureExtractor | ML Preprocessing | Normalize data, build feature vectors |
| MLInference | Classification | Load model, execute inference, return risk level |
| HazardDetector | Decision Making | Combine ML with rules, determine alert level |
| AlertManager | User Feedback | Map risk to LED patterns, control GPIO |

#### 2.1.4 Data Flow {#2.1.4-data-flow}

The system data flow proceeds as follows:

1. Sensors (MPU6500, QMC5883L, NEO-6M) collect raw measurements via I2C/UART  
2. Sensor fusion combines accelerometer, gyroscope, magnetometer, and GPS data  
3. V2VMessage builder populates 90-byte BSM structure with current state  
4. ESP-NOW broadcasts message to all peers at 10Hz  
5. Received peer messages are deduplicated and stored  
6. Feature extractor builds 30-dimensional vector from ego \+ peer states  
7. ML model classifies hazard by braking level  
8. Alert manager updates LED based on risk

### 2.2 The Life Cycle of the System {#2.2-the-life-cycle-of-the-system}

#### 2.2.1 System States {#2.2.1-system-states}

The system operates through defined states:

- **POWER ON**: Initial boot  
- **SELF-TEST**: Component diagnostics (IMU, GPS, Network, SD Card)  
- **GPS ACQUIRING**: Waiting for satellite fix (LED slow blink)  
- **OPERATIONAL**: Normal operation (LED off, 10Hz broadcast)  
- **LOGGING**: Data collection active (LED solid on)  
- **ERROR**: Component failure (system continues with degraded capability)

![][image5]

#### 2.2.2 Initialization Sequence {#2.2.2-initialization-sequence}

1. Initialize Serial Logger (115200 baud)  
2. Initialize I2C Bus (400 kHz, SDA=21, SCL=22)  
3. Initialize MPU6500 (WHO\_AM\_I check, configure ±4g/±500dps, load calibration)  
4. Initialize QMC5883L (I2C address 0x0D, continuous mode)  
5. Initialize NEO-6M GPS (UART1, RX=16, TX=17, 9600 baud)  
6. Initialize ESP-NOW (WiFi STA mode, channel 1, register callbacks, add broadcast peer)  
7. Initialize SD Card (SPI, CS=5, create /logs directory)  
8. Enter Main Loop

#### 

#### 2.2.3 Main Loop Cycle (100ms period) {#2.2.3-main-loop-cycle-(100ms-period)}

Each 100ms cycle performs:

1) **Update GPS parser**  
    Drain UART buffer and update cached GPS state.

2) **Build local V2VMessage**  
   Populate a V2VMessage structure with the node’s current sensor-derived vehicle state.

3) **Mesh participation via ESP-NOW**  
* Broadcast the locally generated V2VMessage with hopCount \= 0.  
* Process all received V2V messages since the previous cycle:  
  * Validate message integrity and freshness.  
  * Discard duplicate messages using (sourceMAC, timestamp) tracking.  
  * For valid, non-duplicate messages with hopCount \< MAX\_HOPS, rebroadcast the message with incremented hopCount.  
* Maintain a bounded cache of recently seen messages to prevent forwarding loops and broadcast storms.

#### 2.2.4 Error Handling {#2.2.4-error-handling}

| Error Condition | Recovery Action |
| :---- | :---- |
| IMU Init Failure | Log error, continue without IMU |
| GPS Init Failure | Log error, continue without GPS |
| Network Init Failure | Halt system (critical) |
| SD Card Failure | Disable logging, continue operation |
| GPS Signal Loss | Use cached position (up to 30s) |
| Write Failure | Retry 3x, then stop logging |

## 3\. Literature Survey {#3.-literature-survey}

### 3.1 V2V Communication and Protocol Standards

The foundation of Vehicle-to-Vehicle (V2V) systems lies in the ability to exchange data with high reliability and minimal delay. According to Kenney (2011), the standard for such interactions in the United States is Dedicated Short-Range Communications (DSRC), which utilizes the IEEE 802.11p PHY/MAC layer to ensure low-latency performance. Technical literature emphasizes that collision avoidance requires message delivery within 100ms to provide human drivers or automated agents sufficient reaction time.  
A critical component of this communication is the SAE J2735 standard, which defines the Basic Safety Message (BSM). As specified in the sources, the BSM Part I contains essential vehicle state data—such as position, velocity, and heading—while Part II allows for application-specific extensions. However, implementing full DSRC hardware is often cost-prohibitive for academic research, with units ranging from $500 to $2000 each. Consequently, the use of ESP-NOW is a viable alternative for prototyping, as it provides connectionless communication with observed latencies of 10–50ms, fitting within the safety-critical 100ms window.

### 3.2 Sensor Fusion and Orientation Estimation

Accurate hazard detection is impossible without precise orientation and positioning data. Traditional sensors like GPS often suffer from a 3–5m error margin and low update rates (typically 1Hz), which cannot distinguish between lanes in close proximity. To mitigate this, the literature suggests fusing high-frequency Inertial Measurement Unit (IMU) data with absolute GPS coordinates.  
A pivotal work in this field by Madgwick (2010) describes an efficient orientation filter for inertial/magnetic sensor arrays that allows for tilt-compensated, stable yaw angles. The SafeRide system adopts a similar approach, combining MPU6500 (6-axis IMU) and QMC5883L (magnetometer) data to achieve 9-axis functionality, which provides improved interference isolation and placement flexibility compared to integrated units.

### 3.3 Embedded Machine Learning and Model Quantization

Deploying complex hazard detection models on resource-constrained hardware like the ESP32 (which has only 520KB SRAM) requires aggressive optimization. Krishnamoorthi (2018) details the necessity of quantizing deep convolutional networks to enable efficient inference on edge devices. By converting models from float32 to INT8 precision, researchers can achieve a 4x reduction in model size with a typical accuracy loss of only 2–5%.  
Furthermore, the challenge of limited real-world training data is often addressed through Domain Randomization. As noted by Tobin et al. (2017), transferring neural networks from simulation to the real world is made more robust by augmenting datasets with synthetic variations. The SafeRide project implements this by collecting real world data conditions by recording a drive as a base scenario, then augmenting said scenario with dozens of synthetic variations, adjusting parameters like speed scaling (±10%) and position jitter (±2m) to improve model generalisation.

### 3.4 Discussion: Technology Selection and Feasibility

The literature confirms that standards-compliant V2V hazard detection is feasible on low-cost hardware by leveraging TensorFlow Lite Micro for embedded inference and SAE J2735-compatible messaging. While the system is not intended for production-grade safety certification (such as ISO 26262), it serves as a robust research prototype for demonstrating multi-scenario detection (convoy, intersection, and lane changes) with an accuracy target of \>85%.

### References:

-   **Krishnamoorthi, R**.: "Quantizing deep convolutional networks for efficient inference", arXiv:1806.08342, 2018 \- Quantization best practices  
- **Madgwick, S.O.H**.: "An efficient orientation filter for inertial and inertial/magnetic sensor arrays", University of Bristol, 2010 \- IMU sensor fusion algorithm  
- **Kenney, J.B**.: "Dedicated Short-Range Communications (DSRC) Standards in the United States", Proceedings of the IEEE, Vol. 99, No. 7, 2011 \- V2V technology overview  
- **SAE J2735**: "Dedicated Short Range Communications (DSRC) Message Set Dictionary", SAE International, 2016 \- Defines Basic Safety Message format  
- **TensorFlow Lite Documentation**: https://www.tensorflow.org/lite \- Framework for model quantization and embedded deployment  
- **ESP32 Technical Reference Manual**, Espressif Systems, 2023 \- Hardware platform specifications

### 3.2 Solution Survey {#3.2-solution-survey}

As established in the Problem Survey, the system must overcome high communication latency, sensor inaccuracies, and severe hardware constraints to achieve reliable hazard detection. The following solutions have been selected based on their prevalence in technical literature and their ability to address these specific problems.

### 3.2.1 Solutions for Communication and Latency

To solve the latency problem where traditional WiFi overhead (100–500ms) exceeds the 100ms safety-critical window for collision avoidance, the system utilizes ESP-NOW.

* ESP-NOW Protocol: This connectionless protocol bypasses the handshake requirements of standard IEEE 802.11, reducing latency to 10–50ms. This directly enables the "real-time" requirement for safety messages while operating on low-cost hardware.  
* Mesh Networking and Relay: To address the limited range of peer-to-peer signals in urban environments, multi-hop relaying is implemented. By using hop-count limiting (2–3 hops) and deduplication via source MAC and timestamps, the system extends its coverage area without causing "broadcast storms" or network flooding.

### 3.2.2 Solutions for Messaging Interoperability 

To mitigate the problem of non-standard protocols used in baseline research, the system adopts industry-recognised formatting.

* SAE J2735 BSM Format: Following the overview by Kenney (2011), the system implements the Basic Safety Message (BSM) structure. By packing core state data (position, speed, heading) into BSM Part I and application-specific hazard classifications into Part II, the system remains under the 250-byte wireless payload limit while ensuring potential interoperability with international V2V standards.

### 3.2.3 Solutions for Sensor Accuracy and Fusion

To solve the problem regarding GPS errors (3–5m) and IMU drift, the system employs a multi-modal fusion approach.

* Complementary Filtering: This method addresses IMU drift by using weighted blending to combine high-frequency accelerometer/gyroscope data with low-frequency, absolute GPS updates.  
* 9-Axis Orientation (Madgwick Algorithm): To solve the issue of unreliable heading at low speeds (where GPS velocity is insufficient), the system integrates the QMC5883L magnetometer. By applying the orientation filter proposed by Madgwick (2010), the system achieves a tilt-compensated, stable yaw angle necessary for predicting converging trajectories in intersection scenarios.  
* Sensor data recorded from real-world drives which provides a more accurate measure of sensor drift and accuracy.

### 3.2.4 Solutions for Resource-Constrained ML 

The literature identifies limited SRAM (520KB) and generalisation across scenarios as primary barriers to embedded intelligence.

* TensorFlow Lite Micro & INT8 Quantization: As suggested by Krishnamoorthi (2018), the system applies 8-bit integer quantization, which reduces the model size by 4x with a minimal accuracy loss (typically 2–5%). This allows complex models to fit within the ESP32’s memory alongside the networking stack.  
* Multi-Class Neural Networks: To move beyond the single-scenario limitation of rule-based systems, a dense neural network architecture is used. By training on 30-dimensional vectors (comprising ego and peer states), the model can generalise across diverse scenarios such as convoys, intersections, and lane changes.  
* Domain Randomization for Data Augmentation: To solve the problem of limited real-world training data, the system adopts the methodology of Tobin et al. (2017), augmenting real trials with synthetic variations in simulation to improve model robustness.

### 3.3 Discussion and Conclusion {#3.3-discussion-and-conclusion}

#### 3.3.1 Technology Selection Rationale {#3.3.1-technology-selection-rationale}

**ESP-NOW over IEEE 802.11p**: Hardware cost of $500-2000 per 802.11p unit exceeds student budgets. ESP-NOW provides equivalent connectionless broadcast at $5-10 per unit with application-layer message compatibility.

**MPU6500 \+ QMC5883L**: The combination of 6-axis IMU with separate magnetometer provides equivalent 9-axis functionality with improved placement flexibility and interference isolation.

**TensorFlow Lite**: Mature framework with extensive tooling for conversion and quantization, avoiding significant custom development effort.

#### 3.3.2 Design Trade-offs {#3.3.2-design-trade-offs}

| Decision | Rationale |
| :---- | :---- |
| 10Hz broadcast | Balances latency with bandwidth |
| 90-byte message | Includes necessary fields with extension room |
| INT8 quantization | 4x size reduction, \<5% accuracy loss |
| CSV logging | Human-readable, ML tool compatible |
| Single-core execution | Sufficient performance, simpler synchronization |

#### 3.3.3 Conclusions {#3.3.3-conclusions}

The literature confirms feasibility of standards-compliant V2V hazard detection on low-cost embedded hardware. Key enablers include ESP-NOW for adequate latency, TensorFlow Lite for embedded ML, sensor fusion for robustness, and SAE J2735 for interoperability.

## 4\. Design

### 4.1 Machine Learning Design

This section defines the ML subsystem of the SafeRide V2V Hazard Alert System, including simulation-first data generation, labeling, reinforcement-learning training, evaluation, deployment, and firmware integration.  
**Only one vehicle executes ML; other vehicles are broadcast-only non-intelligent peers.**

### 4.1.1 Problem Definition

#### 4.1.1.1 Objective

Estimate **riskLevel ∈ {0–3}** for brake-alert situations based on:

* Ego sensors (IMU, magnetometer when available, GPS)

* Peer V2V messages (V2VMessage, \~90 bytes)

* ESP-NOW links (10–50 ms latency, ≤250-byte payloads)  
  

  ### 

  ### 

  #### 4.1.1.2 Outputs

* `alert.riskLevel ∈ {0,1,2,3}`

* `alert.confidence ∈ [0,1]`

  #### 4.1.1.3 Performance Targets

| Metric | Target |
| :---- | :---- |
| Accuracy | ≥ 85% |
| Collision-rate reduction | ≥ 30% |
| Inference time | \< 10 ms |
| End-to-end latency | \< 100 ms |
| Model size | \< 40 KB |
| Tensor arena | 10 KB |


  ### 4.1.2 Simulation Data Pipeline & Labeling

  #### 4.1.2.1 Scenario Families (SUMO \+ ESP-NOW Emulator)

Data is generated using **SUMO 1.25+** with **network impairments injected by the ESP-NOW Emulator Class** to match measured hardware distributions.

**Traffic Scenarios**

* Convoy following & braking

* Cut-in / cut-out

* Intersections (straight, turning)

* Merges

* Curves / hills

* Speed-limit transitions

* Stop-and-go waves

**Edge Scenarios**

* Multi-peer (2–5 neighbors)

* Sensor degradation (GPS noise, dropouts)

* Network impairments (latency 10–80 ms, jitter 0–30 ms, loss 0–10%)

**Parameter Sweeps**

* Ego speed: 0–30 m/s

* Peer speed: 0–35 m/s

* Headway: 0.5–3.0 s

* Braking: 0.5–6 m/s²

* Friction μ: 0.3–1.0

* Seeds: ≥ 5–10 per variation

    
  


  #### 4.1.2.2 Ground-Truth Labeling (TTC / THW)

TTC and THW are latency-shifted to reflect real ESP-NOW behavior.

| Condition | Label |
| :---- | ----- |
| TTC \> 6 s | 0 (None) |
| 4–6 s TTC or 1.5–2.0 s THW | 1 (Low) |
| 2–4 s TTC or 1.0–1.5 s THW | 2 (Medium) |
| TTC ≤ 2 s or THW ≤ 1.0 s | 3 (High) |

#### 4.1.2.3 V001 Logging Specification

**Rate: 10 Hz**

V001 logs:

* Timestamp

* **Ego GPS:** lat/lon/alt, speed, heading, HDOP, GPS-age

* **Ego IMU/mag:** accel, gyro, mag

* **Derived:** longitudinal/lateral acceleration

* **Up to 2 peers:**

  * ID, position, speed, heading, accel

  * hopCount (always 0\)

  * age\_ms (packet age)

* Offline-computed TTC, relative distance, relative speed

**Important Notes**

* Simulation-only fields (RSSI, loss, perfect ground truth) are **not** logged on hardware unless receive-side logging is later added.

**Dataset Metadata**

* Scenario config \+ seed

* Git hashes (simulation, firmware, training)

* Frame count

### 4.1.3 Feature Engineering (30-Dim Input)

Matches **ML\_FEATURE\_COUNT \= 30**

#### 4.1.3.1 Ego Features (10)

1. Speed

2. Longitudinal acceleration

3. Lateral acceleration

4. Heading

5. Speed ratio (simulation-only)

6. Braking flag

7. GPS age

8. GPS HDOP

9. Peer count

10. Max decel (past 1 s)

    #### 4.1.3.2 Peer Features (2 × 10 \= 20\)

For the two closest peers:

1. Relative distance

2. Lateral offset

3. Relative speed

4. Relative heading

5. TTC estimate

6. Peer acceleration

7. Packet age (ms)

8. hopCount (always 0\)

9. Peer riskLevel (reserved)

10. Exists flag

    #### 4.1.3.3 Normalization / Missing Data

* Means/stds in `normalization.json`

* Missing peers → padded features \+ exists\_flag \= 0

* Stale GPS → last valid fix \+ GPS-age

  ### 4.1.4 Learning Method (RL-Only)

**Supervised learning removed** — the system uses **Reinforcement Learning as the sole learning approach.**

#### 4.1.4.1 Reinforcement Learning (Primary & Only Method)

#### **Agent & Opponents**

* **Agent:** V001

* **Opponents:** SUMO IDM vehicles

  #### **Action Space**

Two formulations supported during training:

1. **Discrete riskLevel prediction**: {0,1,2,3}

2. **(Alternative curriculum)** Discrete deceleration bins: {0, 1, 2.5, 4 m/s²}

   #### **Reward Function**

* −1.0 collision

* −0.2 near miss (TTC ≤ 1.5 s)

* −0.05 unnecessary High alerts

* \+progress

* \+early-warning bonus

  #### **Safety Overrides (Firmware & Simulation)**

* If TTC \< 1.0 s → **force High**

* Stale peers → rule-based fallback

* ML failure → fallback heuristic

  #### 4.1.4.2 Domain Randomization

* Traffic density

* Road geometry

* Network impairments

* Sensor noise

* GPS dropouts

* IMU calibration drift

* Random seeds logged

## 4.2 Data Design {#4.2-data-design}

### 4.2.1 Database Description {#4.2.1-database-description}

**Non-Volatile Storage (NVS):**

| Namespace | Key | Type | Description |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| calibration | accel\_offset\_x/y/z | float | Accelerometer offsets (m/s²) |
| calibration | gyro\_offset\_x/y/z | float | Gyroscope offsets (rad/s) |
| calibration | mag\_hard\_iron\_x/y/z | float | Magnetometer offsets (μT) |
| calibration | is\_calibrated | bool | Calibration validity |
| datalogger | session\_number | uint16 | Logging session counter |

### 4.1.2 Global Data Structures Design {#4.1.2-global-data-structures-design}

**V2VMessage (90 bytes total):**

| Section | Fields | Size |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Header | version (1), vehicleId (8), timestamp (4) | 13 bytes |
| Position | lat, lon, alt (floats) | 12 bytes |
| Dynamics | speed, heading, longAccel, latAccel (floats) | 16 bytes |
| Sensors | accel\[3\], gyro\[3\], mag\[3\] (floats) | 36 bytes |
| Alert | riskLevel (1), scenarioType (1), confidence (4) | 6 bytes |
| Mesh | hopCount (1), sourceMAC (6) | 7 bytes |

**ImuData Structure:**

- accel\[3\]: Acceleration in m/s² (X, Y, Z)  
- gyro\[3\]: Angular velocity in rad/s (X, Y, Z)  
- mag\[3\]: Magnetic field in μT (X, Y, Z)  
- timestamp: Milliseconds since boot

**GpsData Structure:**

- latitude/longitude: WGS84 coordinates (double)  
- altitude: Meters above sea level (float)  
- speed: Ground speed in m/s (float)  
- heading: True heading 0-359 degrees (float)  
- valid: GPS fix validity (bool)  
- satellites: Number in view (uint8)  
- hdop: Horizontal dilution of precision (float)  
- cached: Using cached data flag (bool)

### 4.3 Structural Design {#4.3-structural-design}

#### 4.3.1 Class Diagram {#4.3.1-class-diagram}

The system consists of the following classes organized by layer:

**Interfaces:**

- IImuSensor: Abstract IMU interface with begin(), read(), calibrate(), loadCalibration(), saveCalibration(), isCalibrated(), getName()  
- IGpsSensor: Abstract GPS interface with begin(), read(), update(), hasEverHadFix(), getName()  
- ITransport: Abstract transport interface with begin(), send(), onReceive(), getMaxPayload(), getName(), isReady()

**Sensor Implementations:**

- MPU6500Driver implements IImuSensor: I2C communication with MPU6500, offset calibration, NVS storage  
- NEO6M\_Driver implements IGpsSensor: UART parsing with TinyGPSPlus, 4-state cache logic  
- QMC5883LDriver: I2C magnetometer with hard/soft iron calibration

**Network Components:**

- EspNowTransport implements ITransport: Singleton with ESP-NOW initialization, broadcast, callbacks  
- PackageManager: Message deduplication using MAC+timestamp, FIFO eviction, 20 MAC limit  
- V2VMessage: 90-byte BSM structure with validation methods

**Application Components:**

- FeatureExtractor: Builds 30-dimensional feature vectors from vehicle states  
- MLInference: TFLite interpreter wrapper with 10KB tensor arena  
- HazardDetector: Orchestrates ML inference, combines with rules  
- AlertManager: LED pattern control based on risk level

**Utilities:**

- Logger: Singleton with log levels (DEBUG, INFO, WARNING, ERROR)  
- DataLogger: SD card CSV logging with buffered writes

### 4.4 Interactions Design {#4.4-interactions-design}

#### 4.4.1 Use Cases {#4.4.1-use-cases}

| Use Case | Actor | Description |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Receive Collision Warnings | Driver | Driver will receive alerts indicating hazard level |
| View System Status | Driver | Driver observes status LED to verify system health (GPS lock, V2V active, peer count) |
| Broadcast Vehicle State | System | Transmit own vehicle position, speed, heading, acceleration via ESP-NOW |
| Receive Peer Vehicle Data | Other Vehicles | Listen for V2VMessages from nearby SafeRide-equipped vehicles |
| Detect Hazards | System | Machine learning model analyzes multi-vehicle data to classify collision risk |

![][image7]

#### 4.4.2 Sequence Diagram {#4.4.2-sequence-diagram}

**Hazard Detection Sequence:**

1. Main Loop calls MPU6500Driver.read() → returns ImuData  
2. Main Loop calls NEO6M\_Driver.read() → returns GpsData  
3. Main Loop calls FeatureExtractor.setEgoState() with sensor data  
4. For each peer message: FeatureExtractor.addPeerState()  
5. FeatureExtractor.extractFeatures() → returns float\[30\]  
6. MLInference.infer(features) → returns RiskLevel  
7. AlertManager.setRisk(level) → updates LED pattern

![][image8]  
**V2V Message Exchange:**

1. Vehicle A: buildV2VMessage() creates 90-byte structure  
2. Vehicle A: transport.send() broadcasts via ESP-NOW  
3. Vehicle B: onDataReceived() callback triggered  
4. Vehicle B: Validate message size \== 90  
5. Vehicle B: PackageManager.isDuplicate() check  
6. Vehicle B: PackageManager.addPackage() if new  
7. Vehicle B: Update peer state for ML

![][image9]

#### 4.4.3 Activity Diagram {#4.4.3-activity-diagram}

**Main Operation Flow Summary:**  
**Startup Phase (ONE TIME):**

1) Initialize Hardware → GPIO, LED, I2C configuration  
2) Initialize IMU (MPU6500)  
- Success → Continue  
- Failure → Yellow LED warning (degraded mode, continue without IMU)  
3) Initialize GPS (NEO6M)  
- Success → Continue  
- Failure → Yellow LED warning (IMU-only mode, continue)  
4) Initialize ESP-NOW (V2V mesh)  
- Success → Continue  
- Failure → Red LED \+ HALT SYSTEM (critical \- cannot operate without V2V)  
5) Wait for GPS Lock (15-60s cold start)  
- Acquired → Green LED (full operational)  
- Timeout → Yellow LED (proceed with IMU-only positioning)  
6) Enter Main Loop

**Main Loop (10Hz \- Every 100ms):**

1) Read Sensors  
- MPU6500: Accelerometer \+ Gyroscope (x,y,z)  
- NEO6M: Position (lat/lon), speed, heading  
2) Build V2VMessage (90 bytes, SAE J2735 BSM format)  
- Pack sensor data \+ vehicle state  
3) Broadcast via ESP-NOW  
- Send to all peers (FF:FF:FF:FF:FF:FF broadcast)  
4) Process Received V2V Messages  
- Validate message (timestamp freshness \<500ms)  
- Deduplicate (check sourceMAC \+ timestamp hash)  
- Update peer vehicle states in memory  
5) Collision Detection (if peers available)  
- Extract Features: Ego \+ peer states → 30 features  
- ML Inference: TFLite model (\<50ms latency target)  
- Risk Classification:  
  \- None → Continue (Green LED)  
  \- Low → Yellow LED slow blink (1Hz)  
  \- Medium → Yellow LED fast blink (5Hz)  
  \- High → Red LED \+ Buzzer (continuous alert)  
6) Update Status LED  
- GPS lock: Solid (locked) / Blinking (searching)  
- Peer count: Blink pattern (1-3 blinks \= peer count)  
- System health: Green (OK) / Yellow (degraded) / Red (critical)  
7) Delay 100ms → Loop back to step 1

![][image10]

### 4.5 Software Architecture Pattern {#4.5-software-architecture-pattern}

#### 4.5.1 Three-tier: Data, Logic and Presentation tiers {#4.5.1-three-tier:-data,-logic-and-presentation-tiers}

**Presentation Tier:**

- AlertManager: LED pattern output on GPIO 2  
- Risk level mapping: NONE=OFF, LOW=slow blink, MEDIUM=fast blink, HIGH=solid  
- Serial Logger: Debug output at 115200 baud

**Logic Tier:**

- HazardDetector: Orchestrates detection, combines ML with rules  
- FeatureExtractor: Builds 30-dim feature vectors, normalizes inputs  
- MLInference: TFLite model execution, \<100ms inference  
- VehicleState: Aggregates sensor data, tracks peers  
- PackageManager: Deduplicates messages, enforces limits  
- MessageBuilder: Populates V2VMessage, validates format

**Data Tier:**

- Sensor Drivers: MPU6500Driver (I2C 0x68), NEO6M\_Driver (UART1), QMC5883LDriver (I2C 0x0D)  
- Network: EspNowTransport (WiFi 2.4GHz), V2VMessage (90 bytes)  
- Storage: NVS (calibration), DataLogger (SD Card CSV)

#### 4.4.2 MVC: Model, View, Controller structure {#4.4.2-mvc:-model,-view,-controller-structure}

**Model:**

- Data Structures: V2VMessage, ImuData, GpsData, PackageData, RiskLevel, ScenarioType  
- Data Access: Sensor drivers, EspNowTransport, PackageManager, NVS, DataLogger

**View:**

- AlertManager: LED output patterns  
- Logger: Serial debug output with timestamps and levels

**Controller:**

- Main Loop (main.cpp): setup() initializes components, loop() executes 10Hz cycle  
- Callbacks: onDataReceived() processes peer messages  
- Application Logic: HazardDetector, FeatureExtractor, MLInference

3. Execute test suite (\~30 seconds)  
4. Verify all tests pass  
5. Flash production firmware

Model embedded on V001, inference tuning.

Emulator → firmware closed loop; regression tests.  
Exit: Stable behavior across all scenarios.

W35–W40 — Field Tests \+ Hardening

Outdoor tests, calibration refinements, power/SD robustness, final docs.  
Exit: ≥10 validated field runs, final report complete.
